<p><b>Automobili Lamborghini S.p.A.</b> (<small>Italian:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Italian" title="Help:IPA for Italian">[lamborˈɡiːni]</a></span><small class="nowrap metadata">&#160;(<a href="/wiki/File:De-Lamborghini-pronunciation.ogg" title="File:De-Lamborghini-pronunciation.ogg"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/13px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png" width="13" height="13" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/20px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/26px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="500" /></a> <a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d6/De-Lamborghini-pronunciation.ogg" class="internal" title="De-Lamborghini-pronunciation.ogg">listen</a>)</small>) is an Italian brand and manufacturer of luxury <a href="/wiki/Sports_car" title="Sports car">sports cars</a> and <a href="/wiki/SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="SUV">SUVs</a> based in <a href="/wiki/Sant%27Agata_Bolognese" title="Sant'Agata Bolognese">Sant'Agata Bolognese</a>, Italy. The company is owned by the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> through its subsidiary <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a>.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Ferruccio_Lamborghini" title="Ferruccio Lamborghini">Ferruccio Lamborghini</a>, an Italian <a href="/wiki/Business_magnate" title="Business magnate">manufacturing magnate</a>, founded Automobili Ferruccio Lamborghini S.p.A. in 1963 to compete with established marques, including <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a>. The company gained wide acclaim in 1966 for the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Miura" title="Lamborghini Miura">Miura</a> sports <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a>, which established <a href="/wiki/Rear_mid-engine,_rear-wheel-drive_layout" title="Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout">rear mid-engine, rear wheel drive</a> as the standard layout for high-performance cars of the era. Lamborghini grew rapidly during its first decade, but sales plunged in the wake of the <a href="/wiki/1973%E2%80%931974_stock_market_crash" class="mw-redirect" title="1973–1974 stock market crash">1973 worldwide financial downturn</a> and the <a href="/wiki/1973_oil_crisis" title="1973 oil crisis">oil crisis</a>. The firm's ownership changed three times after 1973, including a bankruptcy in 1978. American <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler Corporation</a> took control of Lamborghini in 1987 and sold it to Malaysian investment group Mycom Setdco and Indonesian group V'Power Corporation in 1994. In 1998, Mycom Setdco and V'Power sold Lamborghini to the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> where it was placed under the control of the group's <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a> division.</p>
<p>New products and model lines were introduced to the brand's portfolio and brought to the market and saw an increased productivity for the brand Lamborghini. In the late 2000s, during the <a href="/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%932010" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial crisis of 2007–2010">worldwide financial crisis</a> and the subsequent economic crisis, Lamborghini's sales saw a drop of nearly 50 percent.</p>
<p>Lamborghini produces sports cars and <a href="/wiki/V12_engine" title="V12 engine">V12 engines</a> for <a href="/wiki/Offshore_powerboat_racing" title="Offshore powerboat racing">offshore powerboat racing</a>. Lamborghini currently produces the V12-powered <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Aventador" title="Lamborghini Aventador">Aventador</a> and the V10-powered <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Hurac%C3%A1n" title="Lamborghini Huracán">Huracán</a>.</p>
<p></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_Lamborghini" title="History of Lamborghini">History of Lamborghini</a></div>
<p>Manufacturing magnate Italian <a href="/wiki/Ferruccio_Lamborghini" title="Ferruccio Lamborghini">Ferruccio Lamborghini</a> founded the company in 1963 with the objective of producing a refined <a href="/wiki/Grand_tourer" title="Grand tourer">grand touring car</a> to compete with offerings from established marques such as <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a>. The company's first models, such as the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_350_GT" title="Lamborghini 350 GT">350 GT</a>, were released in the mid-1960s and were noted for their refinement, power and comfort. Lamborghini gained wide acclaim in 1966 for the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Miura" title="Lamborghini Miura">Miura</a> sports <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a>, which established <a href="/wiki/Rear_mid-engine,_rear-wheel-drive_layout" title="Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout">rear mid-engine, rear wheel drive</a> as the standard layout for high-performance cars of the era.</p>
<p>Lamborghini grew rapidly during its first ten years, but sales plunged in the wake of the <a href="/wiki/1973%E2%80%931974_stock_market_crash" class="mw-redirect" title="1973–1974 stock market crash">1973 worldwide financial downturn</a> and the <a href="/wiki/1973_oil_crisis" title="1973 oil crisis">oil crisis</a>. Ferruccio Lamborghini sold ownership of the company to Georges-Henri Rossetti and René Leimer and retired in 1974. The company went bankrupt in 1978, and was placed in the receivership of brothers Jean-Claude and <a href="/wiki/Patrick_Mimran" title="Patrick Mimran">Patrick Mimran</a> in 1980. The Mimrans purchased the company out of receivership by 1984 and invested heavily in the company's expansion. Under the Mimrans' management, Lamborghini's model line was expanded from the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Countach" title="Lamborghini Countach">Countach</a> to include the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Jalpa" title="Lamborghini Jalpa">Jalpa</a> sports car and the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_LM002" title="Lamborghini LM002">LM002</a> high performance off-road vehicle.</p>
<p>The Mimrans sold Lamborghini to the <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler Corporation</a> in 1987. After replacing the Countach with the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Diablo" title="Lamborghini Diablo">Diablo</a> and discontinuing the Jalpa and the LM002, Chrysler sold Lamborghini to Malaysian investment group Mycom Setdco and Indonesian group V'Power Corporation in 1994. In 1998, Mycom Setdco and V'Power sold Lamborghini to the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> where it was placed under the control of the group's <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a> division. New products and model lines were introduced to the brand's portfolio and brought to the market and saw an increased productivity for the brand Lamborghini. In the late 2000s, during the <a href="/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%932010" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial crisis of 2007–2010">worldwide financial crisis</a> and the subsequent economic crisis, Lamborghini's sales saw a drop of nearly 50 percent.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Products">Products</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Automobiles">Automobiles</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Lamborghini_automobiles" title="List of Lamborghini automobiles">List of Lamborghini automobiles</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Black_Lamborghini_Aventador,_pic1.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG/220px-Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG/330px-Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG/440px-Black_Lamborghini_Aventador%2C_pic1.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4608" data-file-height="3456" /></a>

</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG/220px-2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG/330px-2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG/440px-2014-03-04_Geneva_Motor_Show_1377.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4288" data-file-height="2848" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">

<a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Hurac%C3%A1n" title="Lamborghini Huracán">Huracán</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>As of the 2015 model year, Lamborghini's automobile product range consists of two model lines, both of which are mid-engine two-seat sports cars.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> The V12-powered <a href="/wiki/Aventador" class="mw-redirect" title="Aventador">Aventador</a> line consists of the LP 700–4 coupé and roadster.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> The V10-powered <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Hurac%C3%A1n" title="Lamborghini Huracán">Huracán</a> line currently includes the all-wheel-drive LP 610-4 coupé and roadster, as well as the less powerful rear-wheel-drive LP 580-2 coupé.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> Lamborghini intends to double its car production by producing as many SUVs by 2018 as sports cars.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Marine_engines">Marine engines</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG/220px-Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG/330px-Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG/440px-Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="1200" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mus%C3%A9e_Lamborghini_0071.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
L900 marine engine</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Motori Marini Lamborghini produces a large V12 marine engine block for use in <a href="/wiki/Offshore_powerboat_racing" title="Offshore powerboat racing">World Offshore Series</a> Class 1 powerboats. A Lamborghini branded marine engine displaces approximately 8,171&#160;cc (499&#160;cu&#160;in) and outputs approximately 940&#160;hp (700&#160;kW).<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Lamborghini_motorcycle">Lamborghini motorcycle</span></h3>
<p>In the mid-1980s, Lamborghini produced a limited-production run of a 1,000&#160;cc <a href="/wiki/Sportbike" class="mw-redirect" title="Sportbike">sports</a> motorcycle. UK weekly newspaper <i><a href="/wiki/Motor_Cycle_News" title="Motor Cycle News">Motor Cycle News</a></i> reported in 1994 – when featuring an example available through an <a href="/wiki/Essex" title="Essex">Essex</a> motorcycle retailer – that 24 examples were produced with a Lamborghini <a href="/wiki/Aluminium_alloy" title="Aluminium alloy">alloy</a> frame having <a href="/wiki/Head_tube" title="Head tube">adjustable steering head angle</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kawasaki_GPZ1000RX" title="Kawasaki GPZ1000RX">Kawasaki GPz1000RX</a> engine/transmission unit, <a href="/wiki/Ceriani" title="Ceriani">Ceriani</a> <a href="/wiki/Motorcycle_fork" title="Motorcycle fork">front forks</a> and Marvic wheels. The bodywork was <a href="/wiki/Motorcycle_fairing#Materials" title="Motorcycle fairing">plastic</a> and fully integrated with <a href="/wiki/Motorcycle_fairing" title="Motorcycle fairing">front fairing</a> merged into fuel tank and seat cover ending in a rear tail-fairing. The motorcycles were designed by Lamborghini stylists and produced by French business Boxer Bikes.<sup id="cite_ref-MCN_1994_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MCN_1994-8">[8]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Branded_merchandise">Branded merchandise</span></h3>
<p>Lamborghini licenses its brand to manufacturers that produce a variety of Lamborghini-branded consumer goods including scale models, clothing, accessories, bags, electronics<sup id="cite_ref-merch_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-merch-9">[9]</a></sup> and laptop computers.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg/220px-Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg" width="220" height="138" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg/330px-Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg/440px-Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1403" data-file-height="881" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_miura_svj_spider_4808.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The Miura began as a clandestine prototype, a car that had racing pedigree in a company that was entirely against motorsport.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In contrast to his rival Enzo Ferrari, Ferruccio Lamborghini had decided early on that there would be no factory-supported racing of Lamborghinis, viewing motorsport as too expensive and too draining on company resources.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> This was unusual for the time, as many sports car manufacturers sought to demonstrate the speed, reliability, and technical superiority through motorsport participation. Enzo Ferrari in particular was known for considering his road car business mostly a source of funding for his participation in motor racing. Ferruccio's policy led to tensions between him and his engineers, many of whom were racing enthusiasts; some had previously worked at Ferrari. When Dallara, Stanzani, and Wallace began dedicating their spare time to the development of the P400 prototype, they designed it to be a road car with racing potential, one that could win on the track and also be driven on the road by enthusiasts.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200429_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200429-11">[11]</a></sup> When Ferruccio discovered the project, he allowed them to go ahead, seeing it as a potential marketing device for the company, while insisting that it would not be raced. The P400 went on to become the Miura. The closest the company came to building a true race car under Lamborghini's supervision were a few highly modified prototypes, including those built by factory test driver <a href="/wiki/Bob_Wallace_(test_driver)" title="Bob Wallace (test driver)">Bob Wallace</a>, such as the Miura SV-based "Jota" and the Jarama S-based "Bob Wallace Special".</p>
<p>In the mid-1970s, while Lamborghini was under the management of Georges-Henri Rossetti, Lamborghini entered into an agreement with <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a> to develop, then manufacture 400 cars for BMW in order to meet <a href="/wiki/Group_4_(racing)" title="Group 4 (racing)">Group 4</a> <a href="/wiki/Homologation_(motorsport)" title="Homologation (motorsport)">homologation</a> requirements. BMW lacked experience developing a mid-engined vehicle and believed that Lamborghini's experience in that area would make Lamborghini an ideal choice of partner. Due to Lamborghini's shaky finances, Lamborghini fell behind schedule developing the car's structure and running gear. When Lamborghini failed to deliver working prototypes on time, BMW took the program in house, finishing development without Lamborghini. BMW contracted with <a href="/wiki/Karosserie_Baur" title="Karosserie Baur">Baur</a> to produce the car, which BMW named the <a href="/wiki/BMW_M1" title="BMW M1">M1</a>, delivering the first vehicle in October 1978.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELewin2004119.E2.80.93120_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELewin2004119.E2.80.93120-12">[12]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMitchel2005219_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMitchel2005219-13">[13]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg/220px-Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg/330px-Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg/440px-Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2242" data-file-height="1495" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lotus-Lamborghini_102.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The 1990 <a href="/wiki/Lotus_102" title="Lotus 102">Lotus 102</a> featured a Lamborghini V12.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1985, Lamborghini's British importer developed the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Countach_QVX" title="Lamborghini Countach QVX">Countach QVX</a>, in conjunction with <a href="/wiki/Spice_Engineering" title="Spice Engineering">Spice Engineering</a>, for the 1986 <a href="/wiki/Group_C" title="Group C">Group C</a> championship season. One car was built, but lack of sponsorship caused it to miss the season. The QVX competed in only one race, the non-championship 1986 Southern Suns 500&#160;km race at <a href="/wiki/Kyalami" title="Kyalami">Kyalami</a> in South Africa, driven by <a href="/wiki/Tiff_Needell" title="Tiff Needell">Tiff Needell</a>. Despite the car finishing better than it started, sponsorship could once again not be found and the programme was cancelled.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup></p>
<p>Lamborghini was an engine supplier in <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> for the <a href="/wiki/1989_Formula_One_season" title="1989 Formula One season">1989</a> through <a href="/wiki/1993_Formula_One_season" title="1993 Formula One season">1993 Formula One seasons</a>. It supplied engines to <a href="/wiki/Larrousse" title="Larrousse">Larrousse</a> (1989–1990,1992–1993), <a href="/wiki/Team_Lotus" title="Team Lotus">Lotus</a> (1990), <a href="/wiki/Equipe_Ligier" title="Equipe Ligier">Ligier</a> (1991), <a href="/wiki/Minardi" title="Minardi">Minardi</a> (1992), and to the <a href="/wiki/Modena_(racing_team)" title="Modena (racing team)">Modena</a> team in 1991. While the latter is commonly referred to as a factory team, the company saw themselves as a supplier, not a backer. The 1992 Larrousse–Lamborghini was largely uncompetitive but noteworthy in its tendency to spew oil from its exhaust system. Cars following closely behind the Larrousse were commonly coloured yellowish-brown by the end of the race.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2008)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Lamborghini's best result was achieved with Larrousse at the <a href="/wiki/1990_Japanese_Grand_Prix" title="1990 Japanese Grand Prix">1990 Japanese Grand Prix</a>, when <a href="/wiki/Aguri_Suzuki" title="Aguri Suzuki">Aguri Suzuki</a> finished third on home soil.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup></p>
<p>In late 1991, a Lamborghini Formula One motor was used in the <a href="/wiki/Konrad_KM-011" title="Konrad KM-011">Konrad KM-011</a> <a href="/wiki/Group_C" title="Group C">Group C</a> sports car, but the car only lasted a few races before the project was canceled. The same engine, re-badged a <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler</a>, Lamborghini's then-parent company, was tested by <a href="/wiki/McLaren" title="McLaren">McLaren</a> towards the end of the 1993 season, with the intent of using it during the <a href="/wiki/1994_Formula_One_season" title="1994 Formula One season">1994 season</a>. Although driver <a href="/wiki/Ayrton_Senna" title="Ayrton Senna">Ayrton Senna</a> was reportedly impressed with the engine's performance, McLaren pulled out of negotiations, choosing a <a href="/wiki/Peugeot" title="Peugeot">Peugeot</a> engine instead, and Chrysler ended the project.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Reiter_Lambo.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Reiter_Lambo.jpg/220px-Reiter_Lambo.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Reiter_Lambo.jpg/330px-Reiter_Lambo.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Reiter_Lambo.jpg/440px-Reiter_Lambo.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="800" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Reiter_Lambo.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A Murcielago R-GT participating in the FIA GT Championship at <a href="/wiki/Silverstone_Circuit" title="Silverstone Circuit">Silverstone</a> in 2006</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Two racing versions of the Diablo were built for the Diablo Supertrophy, a single-model racing series held annually from 1996 to 1999. In the first year, the model used in the series was the Diablo SVR, while the Diablo 6.0 GTR was used for the remaining three years.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> Lamborghini developed the Murciélago R-GT as a production racing car to compete in the <a href="/wiki/FIA_GT_Championship" title="FIA GT Championship">FIA GT Championship</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Super_GT" title="Super GT">Super GT</a> Championship and the <a href="/wiki/American_Le_Mans_Series" title="American Le Mans Series">American Le Mans Series</a> in 2004. The car's highest placing in any race that year was the opening round of the FIA GT Championship at <a href="/wiki/Circuit_de_Valencia" class="mw-redirect" title="Circuit de Valencia">Valencia</a>, where the car entered by <a href="/wiki/Reiter_Engineering" title="Reiter Engineering">Reiter Engineering</a> finished third from a fifth-place start.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> In 2006, during the opening round of the Super GT championship at <a href="/wiki/Suzuka_Circuit" title="Suzuka Circuit">Suzuka</a>, a car run by the Japan Lamborghini Owners Club garnered the first victory (in class) by an R-GT. A <a href="/wiki/FIA_GT3_European_Championship" title="FIA GT3 European Championship">GT3</a> version of the Gallardo has been developed by <a href="/wiki/Reiter_Engineering" title="Reiter Engineering">Reiter Engineering</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> A Murciélago R-GT entered by All-Inkl.com racing, driven by <a href="/wiki/Christophe_Bouchut" title="Christophe Bouchut">Christophe Bouchut</a> and Stefan Mücke, won the opening round of the <a href="/wiki/FIA_GT_Championship" title="FIA GT Championship">FIA GT Championship</a> held at <a href="/wiki/Zhuhai_International_Circuit" title="Zhuhai International Circuit">Zhuhai International Circuit</a>, achieving the first major international race victory for Lamborghini.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">Marketing</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Brand_identity">Brand identity</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_logotype.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Lamborghini_logotype.jpg/220px-Lamborghini_logotype.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Lamborghini_logotype.jpg/330px-Lamborghini_logotype.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Lamborghini_logotype.jpg/440px-Lamborghini_logotype.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2176" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_logotype.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The Lamborghini wordmark, as displayed on the back of its cars</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The world of <a href="/wiki/Bullfighting" title="Bullfighting">bullfighting</a> is a key part of Lamborghini's identity.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> In 1962, Ferruccio Lamborghini visited the Seville ranch of <a href="/wiki/Miura_bull" title="Miura bull">Don Eduardo Miura</a>, a renowned breeder of <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Fighting_Bull" title="Spanish Fighting Bull">Spanish fighting bulls</a>. Lamborghini, a <a href="/wiki/Taurus_(astrology)" title="Taurus (astrology)">Taurus</a> himself, was so impressed by the majestic Miura animals that he decided to adopt a raging <a href="/wiki/Bovinae" title="Bovinae">bull</a> as the <a href="/wiki/Emblem" title="Emblem">emblem</a> for the automaker he would open shortly.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESackey200815_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESackey200815-25">[25]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Vehicle_nomenclature">Vehicle nomenclature</span></h3>
<p>After producing two cars with alphanumeric designations, Lamborghini once again turned to the bull breeder for inspiration. Don Eduardo was filled with pride when he learned that Ferruccio had named a car for his family and their line of bulls; the fourth Miura to be produced was unveiled to him at his ranch in Seville.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESackey200815_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESackey200815-25">[25]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200431_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200431-26">[26]</a></sup></p>
<p>The automaker would continue to draw upon the bullfighting connection in future years. The <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Islero" title="Lamborghini Islero">Islero</a> was named for the Miura bull that killed the famed <a href="/wiki/Torero_(bullfighter)" class="mw-redirect" title="Torero (bullfighter)">bullfighter</a> <a href="/wiki/Manolete" title="Manolete">Manolete</a> in 1947. <i>Espada</i> is the Spanish word for <a href="/wiki/Sword" title="Sword">sword</a>, sometimes used to refer to the bullfighter himself. The Jarama's name carried a special double meaning; though it was intended to refer only to the historic bullfighting region in Spain, Ferruccio was concerned about confusion with the also historic <a href="/wiki/Circuito_Permanente_Del_Jarama" class="mw-redirect" title="Circuito Permanente Del Jarama">Jarama motor racing track</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200443_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200443-27">[27]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg/220px-Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg" width="220" height="141" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg/330px-Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg/440px-Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3223" data-file-height="2068" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Diablo_SV_and_Countach.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The Diablo (background) was named for a legendary bull, while the Countach (foreground) broke from the bullfighting tradition.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>After christening the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Urraco" title="Lamborghini Urraco">Urraco</a> after a bull breed, in 1974, Lamborghini broke from tradition, naming the Countach not for a bull,<sup id="cite_ref-lamboregLP500_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lamboregLP500-28">[28]</a></sup> but for <b>contacc</b> (pronounced <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA" title="Help:IPA">[kunˈtɑtʃ]</a></span><small class="nowrap metadata">&#160;(<a href="/wiki/File:Ipa-countach.ogg" title="File:Ipa-countach.ogg"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/13px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png" width="13" height="13" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/20px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/26px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="500" /></a> <a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/73/Ipa-countach.ogg" class="internal" title="Ipa-countach.ogg">listen</a>)</small>),<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> a <a href="/wiki/Piedmontese_language" title="Piedmontese language">Piedmontese</a> expletive.<sup id="cite_ref-lamboregLP500_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lamboregLP500-28">[28]</a></sup> Legend has it that stylist <a href="/wiki/Nuccio_Bertone" title="Nuccio Bertone">Nuccio Bertone</a> uttered the word in surprise when he first laid eyes on the Countach prototype, "Project 112".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELawrence1996183_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELawrence1996183-29">[29]</a></sup> The LM002 (LM for Lamborghini Militaire) sport utility vehicle and the Silhouette (named after the popular racing category of the time) were other exceptions to the tradition.</p>
<p>The Jalpa of 1982 was named for a bull breed; Diablo, for the <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Veragua" class="mw-redirect" title="Duchy of Veragua">Duke of Veragua</a>'s ferocious bull famous for fighting an epic battle against "El Chicorro" in Madrid in 1869;<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200490_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJolliffeWillard200490-30">[30]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lambocarsdia_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lambocarsdia-31">[31]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Murci%C3%A9lago" title="Murciélago">Murciélago</a>, the legendary bull whose life was spared by "El Lagartijo" for his performance in 1879; Gallardo, named for one of the five ancestral castes of the Spanish fighting bull breed;<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup> and Reventón, the bull that defeated young Mexican <i>torero</i> Félix Guzmán in 1943. The <a href="/wiki/Estoque" class="mw-redirect" title="Estoque">Estoque</a> concept of 2008 was named for the <a href="/wiki/Estoc" title="Estoc">estoc</a>, the sword traditionally used by <i>matadors</i> during bullfights.<sup id="cite_ref-EdmundsFirstLook_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EdmundsFirstLook-34">[34]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Concept_vehicles">Concept vehicles</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Lamborghini_concept_vehicles" title="List of Lamborghini concept vehicles">List of Lamborghini concept vehicles</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg/220px-Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg/330px-Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg/440px-Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="960" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Concept_s.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The Concept S, a Gallardo derivative</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Throughout its history, Lamborghini has envisioned and presented a variety of <a href="/wiki/Concept_cars" class="mw-redirect" title="Concept cars">concept cars</a>, beginning in 1963 with the very first Lamborghini prototype, the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_350GTV" title="Lamborghini 350GTV">350GTV</a>. Other famous models include Bertone's 1967 <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Marzal" title="Lamborghini Marzal">Marzal</a>, 1974 <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Bravo" title="Lamborghini Bravo">Bravo</a>, and 1980 <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Athon" title="Lamborghini Athon">Athon</a>, Chrysler's 1987 <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Portofino" title="Lamborghini Portofino">Portofino</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Italdesign" class="mw-redirect" title="Italdesign">Italdesign</a>-styled <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Cala" class="mw-redirect" title="Lamborghini Cala">Cala</a> from 1995, the <a href="/wiki/Zagato" title="Zagato">Zagato</a>-built <a href="/wiki/Zagato_Raptor" title="Zagato Raptor">Raptor</a> from 1996.</p>
<p>A retro-styled <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Miura#2006_Miura_concept" title="Lamborghini Miura">Lamborghini Miura concept car</a>, the first creation of chief designer Walter de'Silva, was presented in 2006. President and CEO Stephan Winkelmann denied that the concept would be put into production, saying that the Miura concept was "a celebration of our history, but Lamborghini is about the future. Retro design is not what we are here for. So we won’t do the [new] Miura.”<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup></p>
<p>At the <a href="/wiki/2008_Paris_Motor_Show" title="2008 Paris Motor Show">2008 Paris Motor Show</a>, Lamborghini revealed the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Estoque" title="Lamborghini Estoque">Estoque</a>, a four-door <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(automobile)" title="Sedan (automobile)">sedan</a> concept. Although there had been much speculation regarding the Estoque's eventual production,<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> Lamborghini management has not made a decision regarding production of what might be the first four-door car to roll out of the Sant'Agata factory.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG/220px-Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG/330px-Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG/440px-Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1920" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Estoque_2.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Estoque" class="mw-redirect" title="Estoque">Estoque</a>, a 2008 sedan concept</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>At the <a href="/wiki/2010_Paris_Motor_Show" title="2010 Paris Motor Show">2010 Paris Motor Show</a>, Lamborghini unveiled the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Sesto_Elemento" title="Lamborghini Sesto Elemento">Sesto Elemento</a>. The concept car is made almost entirely of carbon fibre making it extremely light, weighing only 999&#160;kg. The Sesto Elemento shares the same V10 engine found in the Lamborghini Gallardo. Lamborghini hopes to signal a shift in the company's direction from making super cars focused on top speed to producing more agile, track focused cars with the Sesto Elemento. The concept car can reach 0–62 in 2.5 seconds and can reach a top speed of over 180&#160;mph.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup></p>
<p>At the 2012 Geneva Motor Show, Lamborghini unveiled the Aventador J – a roofless, windowless version of the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Aventador" title="Lamborghini Aventador">Lamborghini Aventador</a>. The Aventador J uses the same 700&#160;hp engine and seven-speed transmission as the standard Aventador.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>At the 2012 Beijing Motor Show, Lamborghini unveiled the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Urus" title="Lamborghini Urus">Urus</a> SUV. This is the first SUV By Lamborghini since the LM002.</p>
<p>As part of the celebration of 50 years of Lamborghini, the company unveiled the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Egoista" title="Lamborghini Egoista">Egoista</a>. <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Egoista" title="Lamborghini Egoista">Egoista</a> is for one person's driving and only one of Egoista is to be made.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup></p>
<p>At the <a href="/wiki/2014_Paris_Motor_Show" title="2014 Paris Motor Show">2014 Paris Motor Show</a>, Lamborghini unveiled the Asterion LPI910-4 hybrid concept car. Named after the actual half-man, half-bull hybrid (<a href="/wiki/Minotaur" title="Minotaur">Minotaur</a>) of Greek legend, it is the first hybrid Lamborghini in the history of the company ("Asterion" was the traditional proper name of another hybrid – namely, . Utilizing the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Hurac%C3%A1n" title="Lamborghini Huracán">Huracán's</a> 5.2 litre V10 producing 607 horsepower, along with one electric motor mounted on the transaxle and an additional two on the front axle, developing an additional 300 horsepower. This puts the power at a combined figure of 907 horsepower. 0–100&#160;km/h is claimed to be "just above 3 seconds," with a claimed top speed of 185&#160;mph.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_affairs">Corporate affairs</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Structure">Structure</span></h3>
<p>As of 2011, Lamborghini is structured as a wholly owned subsidiary of <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">AUDI AG</a> named Automobili Lamborghini S.p.A.<sup id="cite_ref-SpA_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SpA-43">[Notes 1]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2011a62_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2011a62-44">[43]</a></sup></p>
<p>Automobili Lamborghini S.p.A. controls five principal subsidiaries: <a href="/wiki/Ducati" title="Ducati">Ducati Motor Holding S.p.A.</a>, a manufacturer of motorcycles; <a href="/wiki/Italdesign_Giugiaro" title="Italdesign Giugiaro">Italdesign Giugiaro S.p.A.</a>, a 90.1%-owned design and prototyping firm that provides services to the entire Volkswagen Group; MML S.p.A. (Motori Marini Lamborghini), a manufacturer of marine engine blocks; and VOLKSWAGEN GROUP ITALIA S.p.A. (formerly AUTOGERMA S.p.A.), which sells Audi and other Volkswagen Group vehicles in Italy.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2011a62_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2011a62-44">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2012a24_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2012a24-45">[44]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sales_results">Sales results</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg/220px-Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg" width="220" height="90" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg/330px-Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg/440px-Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1979" data-file-height="808" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lamborghini_Gallardo_LP560-4_-_009.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lamborghini Gallardo coupe (Japan)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>By sales, the most important markets in 2004 for Lamborghini's sports cars are the U.S. (41%), Germany (13%), Great Britain (9%) and Japan (8%). Prior to the launch of the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Gallardo" title="Lamborghini Gallardo">Gallardo</a> in 2003, Lamborghini produced approximately 400 vehicles per year; in 2011 Lamborghini produced 1,711 vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2012152_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAUDI_AG2012152-46">[45]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Licensing">Licensing</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Autom.C3.B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam.C3.A9rica">Automóviles Lamborghini Latinoamérica</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg/220px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg/330px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg/440px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1152" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lamborghini Prototype (exterior) by Automóviles Lamborghini Latinoamérica</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Automóviles Lamborghini Latinoamérica <a href="/wiki/S.A._(corporation)" title="S.A. (corporation)">S.A. de C.V.</a></b> (Lamborghini Automobiles of Latin America Public Limited Company) is an authorized distributor and manufacturer of Lamborghini-branded vehicles and merchandise in Latin America and South America.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAutom.C3.B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam.C3.A9rica_S.A._de_C.V1995_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAutom.C3.B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam.C3.A9rica_S.A._de_C.V1995-66">[65]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg/220px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg/330px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg/440px-Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1152" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Autom%C3%B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam%C3%A9rica_Prototype_2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lamborghini Prototype (interior) by Automóviles Lamborghini Latinoamérica</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1995, Indonesian corporation MegaTech, Lamborghini's owner at the time, entered into distribution and license agreements with Mexican businessman Jorge Antonio Fernandez Garcia. The agreements give Automóviles Lamborghini Latinoamérica S.A. de C.V. the exclusive distributorship of Lamborghini vehicles and branded merchandise in Latin America and South America. Under the agreements, Automóviles Lamborghini is also allowed to manufacture Lamborghini vehicles and market them worldwide under the Lamborghini brand.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAutom.C3.B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam.C3.A9rica_S.A._de_C.V1995_66-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAutom.C3.B3viles_Lamborghini_Latinoam.C3.A9rica_S.A._de_C.V1995-66">[65]</a></sup></p>
<p>Automóviles Lamborghini has produced two rebodied versions of the <a href="/wiki/Lamborghini_Diablo" title="Lamborghini Diablo">Diablo</a> called the Eros and the Coatl. In 2015, Automóviles Lamborghini transferred the IP-rights to the Coatl foundation (chamber of commerce no. 63393700) in The Netherlands in order to secure these rights and to make them more marketable.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[66]</a></sup> The company has announced the production of a speedboat called the Lamborghini Glamour.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[67]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Museo_Lamborghini">Museo Lamborghini</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Museo_Lamborghini_(Sant%27Agata_Bolognese,_Bologna,_Italy)_003.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg/220px-Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg/330px-Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg/440px-Museo_Lamborghini_%28Sant%27Agata_Bolognese%2C_Bologna%2C_Italy%29_003.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4000" data-file-height="3000" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Museo_Lamborghini_(Sant%27Agata_Bolognese,_Bologna,_Italy)_003.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Museo Lamborghini</div>
</div>
</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Museo_Lamborghini" title="Museo Lamborghini">Museo Lamborghini</a></div>
<p>This two story museum is attached to the headquarters, and covers the history of Lamborghini cars and sport utility vehicles, showcasing a variety of modern and vintage models. The museum uses displays of cars, engines and photos to provide a history and review important milestones of Lamborghini.</p>
